The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, December 12, 2003  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, Dec. 11: In the wake of increased volatility on the bourses, the BSE has asked its members to exercise caution and be vigilant about activities of their sub-brokers and clients and monitor dealings closely. Members are advised to be vigilant about the activities of their sub-brokers and clients and monitor their dealings closely, including co-relation of their trading activity with the financial and other information provided by them, Rajnikant Patel, chief operating officer of BSE said. It has also asked members to put in place appropriate systems and procedures for monitoring and alert the exchange in case any unusual activity comes to notice.																								 Mumbai, Dec. 11: Larsen amp; Toubro has filed an application with the Bombay High Court for directions to convene a shareholders meeting seeking approval of a scheme of arrangement for demerger of its cement business.																								 New Delhi, Dec. 11: The Lok Sabha today passed a bill seeking the setting up of a national company law tribunal with the government saying that the move would expedite rehabilitation of sick companies which was not possible in the BIFR regime.																								 Chennai, Dec. 11: Kotak Mahindra Bank plans to have at least 50 branches across the country in the next three years and 18 branches by next fiscal, said Uday Kotak, executive vice-chairman and managing director of the bank.																								 New Delhi, Dec. 11: Mauritian firm Twinstar Holdings plan to increase stake in Sterlite Industries does not violate the shareholder agreement it signed with the government for the disinvestment of Balco, the Rajya Sabha was informed today.																								 New Delhi, Dec. 11: The Asian Development Bank is all set to tap the local capital market with its maiden bonds issue amounting to over Rs 455 crore. Its loan sanction to the country would also go up to $1.7 billion.																								 New Delhi, Dec. 11: Minister of state for finance Shripad Naik said today he is confident that the overall tax collection would exceed the budget target of Rs 2,41,460 crore this fiscal.
